export const meta = {
  name: 'eval-provenance-spec-review',
  description: 'Evaluate the Eval-Evidence Provenance spec against the real Composable Beliefs codebase',
  phases: [
    { title: 'Evaluate', detail: 'one agent per spec dimension, each verifying against real code' },
    { title: 'Verify', detail: 'adversarially check each material finding against file:line' },
    { title: 'Synthesize', detail: 'single verdict + design recommendation' },
  ],
}

const REPO = '/Users/mark/dev/repos/mine/amieval/composable-beliefs'

const GROUND_TRUTH = `
You are evaluating a SPEC against the ACTUAL Composable Beliefs (CB) codebase at ${REPO}.
This is a READ-ONLY evaluation. Do NOT edit any files. Verify every claim against real code and cite file:line.

Ground-truth already established (verify, do not trust blindly):
- The schema SSOT is lib/cb/belief.ex (NOT lib/cb/assertion.ex which the spec names; "assertion" was renamed "belief"). The struct field list @fields and serialization order @ordered_keys are a CLOSED list. from_map/to_map only round-trip those keys. _keys tracks present keys and the verifier (lib/cb/schema/verifier.ex check_no_implication_field) actively rejects deleted fields.
- There is NO 'source' field (renamed to 'artifact', a single string URI of form scheme:id matching /^[a-z][a-z0-9_-]*:.+/). The spec's phrase "extend the existing primitive's source/evidence fields" references a field that does not exist.
- There is NO deps.json; deps are an inline list field on each belief. The graph is one file beliefs/beliefs.json (103 beliefs).
- 'evidence' is a list of maps; canonical inner key order is date/detail/artifact/proposed/sent/section (belief.ex @evidence_key_order); EXTRA keys not in that list ARE preserved (order_map appends them sorted). So arbitrary keys can be packed into an evidence entry and survive round-trip, but are not validated or queried.
- 'subjects' is a list of {ref,type} maps; 'tags' is a flat string list. Both are queryable: bs has 'subjects <ref|type>' command and 'subject_type:'/'tag:' list filters (lib/cb/belief/filter.ex, lib/mix/tasks/bs.ex). These are the existing cross-cutting query dimensions.
- artifact-scheme is a CLOSED enum declared in graph contract cb:c040 (kind: enum-registry): current values gmail/session/user/document/source/https/plan. Adding 'eval:' means extending c040's rules[0].values + definitions. Schema discipline is contract cb:c038. kind enum is cb:c039, domain enum cb:c041, status lifecycle cb:c029, conflict scope cb:c032.
- The cascade staleness (lib/cb/belief/graph.ex stale/2 + cmd_stale in bs.ex) flags an active non-primitive whose deps include a SUPERSEDED or RETRACTED belief. It has NO notion of version comparison. Supersession is an explicit act (set old.status=superseded + old.superseded_by). A newly-imported belief does not auto-supersede anything.
- bs tree (lib/cb/belief/formatter.ex tree/2 -> tree_lines) prints, for a primitive, its 'artifact' field and each evidence entry's 'detail' -- but NOT evidence entries' 'artifact'. The detail view DOES print evidence artifact.
- compile-to-NL is lib/cb/output_target.ex driven by output-target contracts (kind: output-target, e.g. cb:c042) consumed by mix cb.generate.claude_md. It renders a FLAT list: each section is a list of belief IDs, each dereferenced to its .claim string. It does NOT do recursive dep traversal (verdict->compound->primitive).
- Write flow: mix cb.preflight (conflict check) -> mix cb.adjudicate -> mix cb.import. Validation runs via mix cb.verify.schema (lib/cb/schema/verifier.ex). CLAUDE.md says beliefs/ must not be modified without explicit user authorization.

The SPEC under review (verbatim summary):
Add ONE capability: an 'eval:' artifact source scheme for PRIMITIVE beliefs carrying structured provenance binding an observation to a (eval_id, run_id, case_id, model, model_version, ruler, outcome+optional value, harness, artifact_ref) tuple. Granularity: one primitive per (run_id, case_id, ruler). Compounds compose across rulers (agreement). Implications are verdicts. Supersession/staleness reuse the existing cascade, with model_version a first-class queryable field so "a newer model_version arrived" flags dependent compounds/implications stale.
New queries: bs list --eval <id>; bs list --model <m> [--version <v>]; filters --case/--ruler/--outcome; bs stale --model-version <model> <old_v>. bs tree must surface each primitive's artifact_ref end-to-end.
Compile: add an 'eval-writeup' target rendering verdict -> compounds -> primitives w/ artifact_refs from a root implication.
Acceptance: (1) create eval: primitive w/ all provenance fields, invalid/missing required fields rejected (validation in schema); (2) query by eval_id, model(+version), case_id, ruler, outcome; (3) compound deps on eval: primitives, bs tree shows full chain to artifact_ref; (4) newer model_version flags dependent compounds/implications stale via existing cascade; (5) compile root implication -> markdown writeup w/ verdict, compounds, primitives+artifact_refs.
Non-goals: no Bittensor/consensus; no numeric-confidence engine; no new storage/UI/service; NO schema redesign or new record type (extend existing primitive); harness/Inspect importer is a follow-up not in scope.
Spec's own implementer note: "If a requirement here seems to need a new subsystem, stop and flag it -- it almost certainly doesn't."
`

const FINDING_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  additionalProperties: false,
  required: ['dimension', 'summary', 'findings'],
  properties: {
    dimension: { type: 'string' },
    summary: { type: 'string', description: '2-3 sentence bottom line for this dimension' },
    findings: {
      type: 'array',
      items: {
        type: 'object',
        additionalProperties: false,
        required: ['title', 'severity', 'kind', 'detail', 'evidence'],
        properties: {
          title: { type: 'string' },
          severity: { type: 'string', enum: ['blocker', 'major', 'minor', 'nit', 'affirm'], description: 'affirm = spec claim is correct/reuse genuinely works' },
          kind: { type: 'string', enum: ['contradiction', 'gap', 'mismatch', 'risk', 'terminology', 'reuse-overstated', 'sizing', 'affirmation'] },
          detail: { type: 'string', description: 'what the issue is and why it matters' },
          evidence: { type: 'string', description: 'concrete file:line citations proving it' },
          recommendation: { type: 'string', description: 'what the implementer should do instead, if applicable' },
        },
      },
    },
  },
}

const VERDICT_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  additionalProperties: false,
  required: ['title', 'standsUp', 'confidence', 'reasoning'],
  properties: {
    title: { type: 'string' },
    standsUp: { type: 'boolean', description: 'true if the finding is accurate after independent code check' },
    confidence: { type: 'string', enum: ['high', 'medium', 'low'] },
    reasoning: { type: 'string', description: 'cite the exact code you checked; note if severity should change' },
    correctedSeverity: { type: 'string', enum: ['blocker', 'major', 'minor', 'nit', 'affirm', 'unchanged'] },
  },
}

phase('Evaluate')

const DIMENSIONS = [
  {
    key: 'data-model',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: Data model fit -- where can the 9 structured provenance fields (eval_id, run_id, case_id, model, model_version, ruler, outcome+value, harness, artifact_ref) actually live, given the CLOSED belief schema?
Read lib/cb/belief.ex fully (@fields, @ordered_keys, @evidence_key_order, from_map, to_map, order_map). Read lib/cb/schema/verifier.ex.
Enumerate the genuinely-viable placement options (e.g. new top-level field(s); pack into an evidence entry's extra keys; map onto subjects {ref,type} + tags + artifact URI path). For EACH option state exactly what code must change, whether it survives JSON round-trip byte-stably, and whether it is queryable by the existing filter/graph layer. Judge the spec's instruction "extend the existing primitive's source/evidence fields; do not create a parallel record type" against what the schema actually permits. Flag that 'source' field does not exist. Decide which option is most CB-native and why.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'validation-schema',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: Validation & the "no schema redesign" tension.
Acceptance #1 requires "invalid/missing required fields are rejected (validation lives with the schema)". Non-goal says "No schema redesign or new record type". Read lib/cb/schema/verifier.ex, lib/cb/belief.ex, and the schema contracts cb:c038 (schema discipline) and cb:c040 (artifact-scheme enum) and cb:c039 in beliefs/beliefs.json (use: cd ${REPO} && python3 -c "import json;b=json.load(open('beliefs/beliefs.json'));idx={x['id']:x for x in b};import sys;print(json.dumps(idx['cb:c038'],indent=1))").
Determine: to REJECT a primitive missing required provenance fields, what must change in (a) belief.ex, (b) verifier.ex, (c) the graph's own schema contracts? Is requiring those fields a "schema redesign" in the sense the non-goal forbids, or a permitted extension? Is acceptance #1 in genuine tension with the non-goal? Separately: the spec calls 'outcome' an "enum" -- but CB closed enums (c039/c040/c041) are GLOBAL, while eval outcomes are per-eval vocabulary (silent_loss/flagged/correct for THIS eval only). Assess whether 'outcome' can be a registered closed enum at all, or must be a free-form string. Also assess how adding the 'eval:' scheme interacts with c040 and whether that edit to beliefs/ is permitted per CLAUDE.md.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'queries',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: Query operations feasibility & sizing.
The spec wants: bs list --eval <id>; bs list --model <m> [--version <v>]; filters --case/--ruler/--outcome. Read lib/cb/belief/filter.ex (parse_args, extract_flags) and lib/mix/tasks/bs.ex (cmd_list, extract_flags) and lib/cb/belief/graph.ex (by_subject).
Determine concretely: (a) if the provenance dims are stored as subjects {ref,type} or tags, do the EXISTING filters (subject_type:, tag:, bs subjects) already satisfy acceptance #2 with zero or near-zero new code? (b) If stored elsewhere, exactly what new filter clauses + flag plumbing are needed? Note that filter.ex uses positional 'key:value' style while the spec writes GNU-style '--eval X' -- assess the mismatch and which convention is cheaper/more consistent. Give a concrete effort estimate (lines/files touched) for each of the 6 query requirements. Identify the simplest design that satisfies acceptance #2.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'staleness-supersession',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: Staleness, supersession, and the model_version pivot -- the spec's riskiest claim.
Read lib/cb/belief/graph.ex (stale/2, cascade_stale, history) and lib/mix/tasks/bs.ex (cmd_stale) and contract cb:c029 (status lifecycle) in beliefs/beliefs.json.
Acceptance #4: "Introducing primitives with a newer model_version flags dependent compounds/implications stale via the existing cascade." Test this against reality: (a) the cascade only fires when a dep is SUPERSEDED/RETRACTED; (b) importing a new belief does NOT auto-supersede an older one; (c) supersession is an explicit status change. So does merely "introducing a newer-model_version primitive" flag anything stale automatically? If not, #4 is false-as-written. (d) Deeper: eval primitives are IMMUTABLE historical facts ("run 3 on case 7 scored silent_loss") -- should they EVER be superseded just because a newer model version exists? Argue what SHOULD go stale (the verdict's reliance on an old model version) vs what the cascade actually supersedes (a dep). (e) The spec separately lists 'bs stale --model-version <model> <old_v>' as a NEW operation -- reconcile: is that the same as "the existing cascade" or a distinct version-comparison mechanism that must be built? Conclude whether acceptance #4 is satisfiable as written, and the minimal correct design for model-version staleness.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'compile-tree',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: bs tree artifact_ref surfacing + eval-writeup compile target.
Read lib/cb/belief/formatter.ex (tree_lines -- exactly what it prints for a primitive: does it print evidence 'artifact'? only 'detail'? the belief's own 'artifact'?) and lib/cb/output_target.ex (compile, render_section -- flat list vs recursive?) and lib/mix/tasks/cb.generate.claude_md.ex.
Determine: (a) Acceptance #3 says bs tree must surface each primitive's artifact_ref. If artifact_ref is stored as the primitive's own 'artifact' field, does tree already show it (cite line)? If stored as an evidence-entry artifact, does tree show it today, or is a formatter change needed? (b) Acceptance #5 / "Compile-to-NL (extend existing)": the existing OutputTarget renders a FLAT section list of claims; the eval-writeup needs verdict->compounds->primitives recursive traversal with artifact_refs. Is this genuinely reusable as "add a template", or is it materially new traversal+render code? Quantify. Judge the spec's framing "if a compile-to-NL pipeline exists, add a template" against the actual flat-list mechanism.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'accuracy-audit',
    prompt: `DIMENSION: Accuracy audit of the spec's claims about what CB "already has" / "reuses unchanged", plus the worked example.
The spec asserts CB "already has" various things and that compounds/implications/supersession "reuse existing CB unchanged / no new code". Audit each such claim against the code. Specifically check the worked example for schema-legality: primitives p1/p2 with artifact "eval:silent-data-loss-v1/run3" -- does that match the artifact regex /^[a-z][a-z0-9_-]*:.+/ (note the '-' in 'silent-data-loss' and '/' chars)? Read lib/cb/schema/verifier.ex check_artifact_format and check_artifact_scheme_enum. Check: can a compound legally depend on primitives (deps rules in verifier check_compound_implication_have_deps)? Does an implication require deps? Is there any rule that a primitive's artifact scheme must be in c040 (yes -- so 'eval:' MUST be added first or every eval primitive fails verify)? List every terminology/factual drift in the spec (assertion.ex, source field, deps.json, "mix bs query shell" naming, etc.) and rate how much each could mislead an implementer. Confirm which spec claims are accurate (affirmations) vs wrong.`,
  },
]

const reviews = await parallel(
  DIMENSIONS.map((d) => () =>
    agent(`${GROUND_TRUTH}\n\n=== YOUR DIMENSION ===\n${d.prompt}\n\nReturn structured findings. Be specific and cite file:line for every claim. Mark severity 'affirm' for spec claims that genuinely hold. Do not edit files.`, {
      label: `eval:${d.key}`,
      phase: 'Evaluate',
      schema: FINDING_SCHEMA,
    })
  )
)

const allFindings = reviews
  .filter(Boolean)
  .flatMap((r) => (r.findings || []).map((f) => ({ ...f, dimension: r.dimension })))

// Verify the consequential findings (blocker/major/contradiction/gap). Affirmations and nits pass through.
const toVerify = allFindings.filter(
  (f) => f.severity === 'blocker' || f.severity === 'major' || f.kind === 'contradiction'
)

phase('Verify')

const verdicts = await parallel(
  toVerify.map((f) => () =>
    agent(`${GROUND_TRUTH}\n\n=== ADVERSARIAL VERIFICATION ===\nAnother evaluator produced this finding about the spec. Independently check it against the ACTUAL code. Try to REFUTE it. Read the cited files yourself. If the evaluator misread the code, say so and set standsUp=false. If correct, confirm and possibly adjust severity.\n\nFINDING TITLE: ${f.title}\nDIMENSION: ${f.dimension}\nSEVERITY: ${f.severity} / KIND: ${f.kind}\nDETAIL: ${f.detail}\nCLAIMED EVIDENCE: ${f.evidence}\nRECOMMENDATION: ${f.recommendation || '(none)'}\n\nReturn a verdict with file:line you personally verified.`, {
      label: `verify:${f.dimension}`,
      phase: 'Verify',
      schema: VERDICT_SCHEMA,
    }).then((v) => ({ finding: f, verdict: v }))
  )
)

const checked = verdicts.filter(Boolean)
const confirmed = checked.filter((c) => c.verdict?.standsUp)
const refuted = checked.filter((c) => c.verdict && !c.verdict.standsUp)

phase('Synthesize')

const synthInput = {
  dimensionSummaries: reviews.filter(Boolean).map((r) => ({ dimension: r.dimension, summary: r.summary })),
  confirmedMaterialFindings: confirmed.map((c) => ({
    title: c.finding.title,
    dimension: c.finding.dimension,
    severity: c.verdict.correctedSeverity === 'unchanged' ? c.finding.severity : c.verdict.correctedSeverity,
    kind: c.finding.kind,
    detail: c.finding.detail,
    evidence: c.finding.evidence,
    recommendation: c.finding.recommendation,
    verifierNote: c.verdict.reasoning,
  })),
  refutedFindings: refuted.map((c) => ({ title: c.finding.title, why: c.verdict.reasoning })),
  affirmationsAndMinor: allFindings
    .filter((f) => f.severity === 'affirm' || f.severity === 'minor' || f.severity === 'nit')
    .map((f) => ({ title: f.title, severity: f.severity, dimension: f.dimension, detail: f.detail })),
}

const synthesis = await agent(
  `${GROUND_TRUTH}\n\n=== SYNTHESIZE THE EVALUATION ===\nYou are the lead reviewer. Below is the verified output of a dimension-by-dimension evaluation of the spec, with adversarial verification already applied (refuted findings are separated out -- do NOT treat them as problems).\n\nProduce a rigorous, decisive engineering evaluation of the spec as a markdown document. Structure:\n1. Verdict (one paragraph): Is the spec sound and buildable mostly-as-described? What is the single biggest correction needed?\n2. What the spec gets right (the genuine reuse -- be concrete and fair).\n3. Blockers & contradictions that must be resolved before implementing (each with the code reality and the fix). Lead with: (i) the closed-schema reality vs "extend source/evidence fields"; (ii) acceptance #1 "validation in schema" vs non-goal "no schema redesign"; (iii) acceptance #4 model_version-staleness "via existing cascade" being false as written.\n4. The recommended data-model design (decide ONE placement for the provenance payload and justify it in CB-native terms: artifact URI + subjects + tags + evidence; specify exactly what, if anything, must be added to belief.ex and the graph's schema contracts).\n5. Required graph/schema changes (the c040 'eval:' scheme addition; any new contract; note the beliefs/ write-authorization requirement).\n6. Effort/sizing per acceptance criterion, and what is genuinely "no new code" vs new code.\n7. Terminology/accuracy corrections the implementer needs (assertion.ex->belief.ex, no source field, no deps.json, etc.).\n8. Recommendation on the implementer note ("if a requirement needs a new subsystem, flag it") -- which requirements trip it.\n\nBe specific, cite file:line where it sharpens a point, and do not pad. This markdown is the deliverable.\n\nINPUT:\n${JSON.stringify(synthInput, null, 2)}`,
  { label: 'synthesize', phase: 'Synthesize' }
)

return {
  synthesis,
  stats: {
    totalFindings: allFindings.length,
    materialVerified: checked.length,
    confirmed: confirmed.length,
    refuted: refuted.length,
  },
  confirmedMaterialFindings: synthInput.confirmedMaterialFindings,
  refutedFindings: synthInput.refutedFindings,
}

